In the Almagest, the third star in Argo is called "The northernmost of the 2 stars close together over the little shield in the poop." The 'little shield' in Greek is ἀσπιδίσκῃ (Aspidiske), sometimes misspelled Azmidi(ske), and the asterism may or may not consist of stars, while the Almagest lists ξ and ο Pup "above" it. According to Allen (1899) The Century Atlas (1897) by Benjamin E. Smith registers ι Arg (now Car) with the name "Aspidiske".

39757.name: Tureis
39757.origin: From the Arabic word al-turais, "the Little Shield," used in the Arabic Almagest in describing several stars (ρ Pup not among them) in the constellation Argo. Wrongly applied as a star name to ρ Pup in recent times.

19780.name: Rhombus
19780.origin: Lacaille named the constellation ''Réticule Rhomboïde'' which may refer to the earlier constellation "Rhombus" that Habrecht (1621) defined in the area.

96757.name: Sham
96757.origin: Applied in recent times from the Arabic constellation name al-sahm, "the Arrow," for Sagitta.

95347.name: Rukbat
95347.origin: Applied in recent times from an abbreviation of its name for the Arabic Almagest period rukbat al-rami, "the Archer's Knee".

95241.name: Arkab Prior
95241.origin: Applied in recent times from an abbreviation of its name for the Arabic Almagest period 'urqub al-rami, "the Archer's Achilles Tendon."

95294.name: Arkab Posterior
95294.origin: Applied in recent times from an abbreviation of its name for the Arabic Almagest period 'urqub al-rami, "the Archer's Achilles Tendon."

88635.name: Alnasl
88635.origin: Applied in recent times from its late Arabic name al-nasl, "the Point," in turn an abbreviation of the Arabic Almagest's nasl al-sahm, "the Point of the Arrow."

89931.name: Kaus Media
89931.origin: Arbitrarily applied in recent times, together with the Latin distinctions of "middle," "southern," and "northern" (for λ Sgr), from the pre-Islamic Arabian (and later Arabic) constellation name al-qaus, "the Bow." For the pre-Islamic Arabians, al-qaus was marked by the curved line of stars ξ2, o, π, d, ρ and u Sgr (corresponding to what in other cultures was Sagittarius among the zodiacal signs). The Arabics used the indigenous name for the Greeks' Archer, alternatively translated as al-rami.

90185.name: Kaus Australis
90185.origin: Arbitrarily applied in recent times, together with the Latin distinctions of "middle," "southern," and "northern" (for λ Sgr), from the pre-Islamic Arabian (and later Arabic) constellation name al-qaus, "the Bow." For the pre-Islamic Arabians, al-qaus was marked by the curved line of stars ξ2, o, π, d, ρ and u Sgr (corresponding to what in other cultures was Sagittarius among the zodiacal signs). The Arabics used the indigenous name for the Greeks' Archer, alternatively translated as al-rami.

93506.name: Ascella
93506.origin: ascella ("armpit"). Although it appeared in the 1515 Almagest, the name does not appear to have come into common usage until the 20th century after appearing as Ascella in Richard Hinckley Allen's "Star Names Their Lore and Meaning" (1899).

90496.name: Kaus Borealis
90496.origin: Arbitrarily applied in recent times, together with the Latin distinctions of "middle," "southern," and "northern" (for λ Sgr), from the pre-Islamic Arabian (and later Arabic) constellation name al-qaus, "the Bow." For the pre-Islamic Arabians, al-qaus was marked by the curved line of stars ξ2, o, π, d, ρ and u Sgr (corresponding to what in other cultures was Sagittarius among the zodiacal signs). The Arabics used the indigenous name for the Greeks' Archer, alternatively translated as al-rami.

89341.name: Polis
89341.origin: the term in Coptic means "a foal." It was originally used for stars in the bow of the Archer but was moved over time.

92761.name: Ainalrami
92761.origin: Arabic عين الرامي ʽain al-rāmī (simplified Ainalrami) means The Eye of the Archer. It originates from Arabic Almagest translations.

94141.name: Albaldah
94141.origin: The name of the 21st Arabic lunar station, البلدة, Al-Baldah (The empty area), designates a starless region between ζ Sgr and α Cap; the star π Sgr is at its northern edge and was wrongly attributed with this name by Allen (1899, 359).

92855.name: Nunki
92855.origin: ᵐᵘˡNUN.KI or ᵐᵘˡNUNᴷᴵ  = the star or constellation of Eridu where Eridu is one of the first big cities known. Archealogical proofs date back to the 3rd millennium (Sumer). It is located at the southern coast of Mesopotamia. The identification of the star or asterism is highly uncertain: it is often identified with Canopus and adjacent areas or "somewhere in Argo". ᵐᵘˡNUN.KI is listed in MUL.APIN and there, it seems to refer to the area of Aquarius with unknown identification (Canopus not excluded) but the identification with other Babylonian texts seems to propose only in the northern part of modern Argo, i.e. Vela. The Euphratean name "Nunki" was mentioned and associated with Sigma Sgr in Robert Brown, Jr. (1892, Proceedings of the Society of Biblical Archaeology, Volume 14, p. 298; "Nun-ki", "Prince-of-the-Earth"), and its use diffused through the 20th century after being mentioned in Richard Hinckley Allen's (Star Names, their lore and meaning, p. 359). The modern Nunki is, thus, not identical with the Sumerian one; it is one of the many misapplications.

98066.name: Terebellum
98066.origin: Ptolemy's Almagest lists four stars in a quadrilateral with ω Sgr the first in the list (the others being A, b, c Sgr). Bayer (1603) concludes this list with the note after "c": Has quatuor multi Terebellum seu τετράπλευρον vocant. A "terebellum" is an auger, so it designates the asterism at the tip of the tail and originally not a specific star.

80763.name: Antares
80763.origin: From its ancient Greek name ἀντάρης, "like Ares", likening the red colour of this star to its planetary namesake (the Roman Mars), name occurs in the Almagest. Possibly the Greek name goes back to a Sumerian precursor AN.TA.GUB (as suggested by Horowitz).

78820.name: Acrab
78820.origin: Arabic name al-'Aqrab for the constellation Scorpius ("the scorpion") (e.g. Al Sufi). Application of the transliteration "Acrab" specifically to the pair Beta1 and Beta2 Sco was made by Piazzi (1814) in the Palermo Catalog, and its use spread through the 19th century.

78401.name: Dschubba
78401.origin: Applied in recent times from an abbreviation of the name for the Arabic Almagest period jabhat al-'aqrab, "the Scorpion's Forehead," for β, δ, and π Sco.

82396.name: Larawag
82396.origin: Larawag is the Wardaman name of ε Sco, from the Northern Territory, Australia. Larawag is part of a procession of beings along the curve of stars in Scorpius, acting as the signal watcher, noting when only legitimate participants are present and in view of the ceremony. He gives the “All clear” signal, allowing the secret part of the ceremony to continue. This procession is related to the bats that carry Ginan.

86228.name: Sargas
86228.origin: MUL.SHAR.GAZ, "mul" is the Sumerian designator for stars and constellations, "Shargaz" and "Sharur" are two weapons of Marduk (the city god of Babylon and highest god of the Babylonian pantheon after 1250 BCE). The line I ii 31-32 in MUL.APIN read: "Two stars which stand in the sting of the Scorpion: Sharur and Shargaz", so these star names have originally been given to the stars lambda and upsilon Sco. The Mesopotamian name "Sargas" was linked to the star Theta Sco by Robert Brown Jr. (1893; "Euphratean Stellar Researches Part II.") and its subsequent mention in R. H. Allen's (1899) "Star-names and Their Meanings" popularized its subsequent use.

85927.name: Shaula
85927.origin: The Arabic lunar mansion "Al Shaula" ("the sting") refers to the pair Lambda and Upsilon Sco (Al Sufi), the two stars that have been called "the sting of the Scorpion" even in MUL.APIN (I ii 31-32) but with different proper names there. "Shaula" appeared more in early modern literature for the pair of stinger stars after Hyde's (1665) translation of Ulugh Beg, and specifically for Lambda Sco after Piazzi's (1814) Palermo Catalog.

82514.name: Xamidimura
82514.origin: Originally spelled as three word "xami di mura" means "eyes of the beast" in the Khoekhoe language (South Africa). The term designates two stars which is why it was suggested (Hahn 1881) to refer to μ Sco as this star appears as a visual pair of two dots of light. Yet, today's identification popularized by the SAAO differs.

82545.name: Pipirima
82545.origin: There are many versions of a widespread Polynesian story of two children fleeing their uncaring parents to become two shining stars, the stars themselves being variously recorded as Castor and Pollux (α and β Gem), Shaula and Lesath (λ and υ Sco), ζ and θ Sco, and µ¹ and µ² Sco as well as [possibly] ω¹ and ω² Sco. In Tahiti, Pipiri was the twin brother of Rehua: Pipiri ma refers to the two together, ma "with, and" being used after names to mean "et al.". Calderon identifies the two children as µ¹ and µ² Sco, their mother being Shaula (λ Sco) and their father Lesath (υ Sco).

79374.name: Jabbah
79374.origin: the name was considered popular by WGSN as mentioned in Allen (1899): "in the Century Cyclopaedia, perhaps from its being one of the mansil Iklil al Jabbah."

78265.name: Fang
78265.origin: determinitive star of lunar mansion Fang (The Room) whose naming constellation constists of 4 stars according to sources back to the 3rd millennium BCE.

78104.name: Iklil
78104.origin: the name derives from the Arabic lunar mansion "Iklil" (Arabic: الإكليل), "The ornamented headband" (or: diadem) composed of the 3 stars β1, δ and π Sco; here misapplied to ρ Sco.

80112.name: Alniyat
80112.origin: Applied in recent times from the pre-Islamic Arabian name al-niyat, "the Arteries", for σ and τ Sco. α Sco, between the arteries, was the pre-Islamic Arabian qalb al'aqrab, "the Scorpion's Heart" (all were part of the pre-Islamic Arabian Scorpion).

81266.name: Paikauhale
81266.origin: Au-haele, Hōkū-‘ula and Paikauhale are documented as three stars in a line, running from north to south. Two of the most reliable sources—Mary Puku‘i and Rubellite Johnson—both identify Hōkū-‘ula as Antares (α Sco), which makes Au-haele Alniyat (σ Sco) and Paikauhale τ Sco.

85696.name: Lesath
85696.origin: The formation of this name begins with the Greek term "(foggy) conglomeration," used by Ptolemy in the Tetrabiblos in describing several nebulous sky objects (in the present case, probably the open cluster M7). Ptolemy's term was translated by the Arabs as al-latkha, "the Spot." This word in turn became transliterated and corrupted in Medieval Latin to alascha, which was used in astrological texts in connection with Scorpius' tail. In Early Modern times, the derivation of alascha was erroneously attributed to the Arabic word las'a, "sting, or bite (of a poisonous animal)," rather than to al-latkha. Subsequently the erroneous word, written as "Lesath," was applied as a star name to u Sco (and in recent times, also to λ Sco).

77070.name: Unukalhai
77070.origin: Applied in recent times from its name for the Arabic Almagest period 'unuq al-hayya, "the Serpent's Neck."

77233.name: Zhou
77233.origin: This is a traditional Chinese star name of one of the stars in the historical Chinese constellation of Tianshi (Celestial Marketplace).

92946.name: Alya
92946.origin: From the Arabic word alya, naming the fatty tail of a breed of Eastern sheep. In Early Modern times this word was erroneously proposed as the origin of Alioth, a Medieval Latin name for ε UMa. The erroneous "Alya" was applied as a star name to θ Ser in recent times.

77450.name: Gudja
77450.origin: Gudja is the Wardaman name of κ Ser, from the Northern Territory, Australia. Gudja is a Water Goanna, related to birth and rebirth. It is part of the bright trio of stars in Serpens Caput, which also include Munin the Rock Cod (γ Ser) and the Mungamungga birthing place (β Ser), likened to a little hospital. Gudja is involved with the birthing process, which includes sacred ritual practices. The Spiritual Women at the birthing and blessing site in Serpens Caput are connected to the sacred areas of Crux and enacted at Munin Rock and Yinggalarri.

21421.name: Aldebaran
21421.origin: Applied in the early Islamic period from its pre-Islamic Arabian name al-dabaran, possibly meaning "the Follower," alternatively used as the lunar mansion name for all the Hyades (or again for α Tau alone). The name is thought to refer to this star's following the Pleiades across the sky, or to the Hyades (or α Tau) coming after the Pleiades as a lunar mansion. "Aldebaran" is one of the oldest Arabic star names applied in the West, from the end of the 10th century A.D.

25428.name: Elnath
25428.origin: From the pre-Islamic Arabian name al-naṭh, "the Butting (with the horns)," an alternative name for the 1st lunar mansion al-sharaṭān consisting of β and γ Ari (see β Ari). Some late Arabic authors also applied al-naṭh  as a star name to α Ari. In recent times the name, as “Nath,” was wrongly transferred to β Tau, and subsequently it was completed to “Elnath” (adding the Arabic definite article).

20205.name: Prima Hyadum
20205.origin: the Latin term occurs first in Flamsteed (1729) but is based on the Arabic idea to enumerate the stars in the cluster; in Arabic it was Awwal ad-Dabarān, The First of Dabarān (the group from which the star name "Aldebaran" derives).

20455.name: Secunda Hyadum
20455.origin: The Latin term Hyadum II goes back to Flamsteed (1729) in analogy to Hyadum I or Prima Hyadum

20889.name: Ain
20889.origin: From an abbreviation of the name for the Arabic Almagest period ain al-thaur "the Bull's Eye," for a Tau. Applied to ε Tau in recent times (Ptolemy had α Tau the southern eye, and ε  Tau on the northern eye).

26451.name: Tianguan
26451.origin: Chinese single star asterism, a celestial pass along the ecliptic which opens and closes

17702.name: Alcyone
17702.origin: These names were individually applied in Early Modern times from a family of characters in Greek mythology: Atlas, Pleione and their seven daughters, the Pleiades.

20894.name: Chamukuy
20894.origin: The Yucatec Maya identify Theta Tauri as chamukuy, the name of a small bird.

8796.name: Mothallah
8796.origin: Applied in recent times from the Arabic constellation name al-muthallath, "the Triangle," for Triangulum.

10064.name: Alaybasan
10064.origin: Al-Aybasān (الأيبسان), the Two Joints (of bones), is an Indigenous Arabian asterism. Name variants are Al-Anīsān (الأنيسان) and Al-Baysan. The later spelling variant al-Anīsān that originated from a mistake changed the meaning, as it translates The Two Friends. WGSN adopts a spelling variant without hyphen: "Alaybasan" is the name for β Tri

10670.name: Apdu
10670.origin: Apd(w), ȝpd, The Bird, is an ancient Egyptian constellation from the second millennium BCE; the language is moribunt. There are at least 21 spelling variants throughout the millennia in hierglyphs, and it is probably not any specific bird; might be a goose or falcon or something else. Four star names within the constellation are attested in Ramesside Star Clocks and identified with the area between α, β Per and all of Triangulum. WGSN adopts the name of the constellation for any unspecific spot within its area to preserve an old Egyptian cultural name.

10644.name: Deltoton
10644.origin: Deltoton (Δελτωτόν; the letter Delta: Δ) is an ancient Greek name variant for the constellation triangulum, probably the original one as "Delta" is the first letter in the ancient Greek term for "dios", the highest god who possesses and rules the stars. In early uranographies, this triangle was considered a sign of the divinity of the starry sky, a divine inscription "written in the stars".

10280.name: Triminus
10280.origin: The star ι Tri (iota or 6 Trianguli) is the brightest one in the early modern variant of a lesser triangle next to the recognisable classical asterism within the constellation Triangulum. The name is composed of the IAU-abbreviation "Tri" and Hevelius's name "Minus" for the lesser triangle. The name applies to the visible dot in the sky, so that "iot Tri A" is "Triminus A". The other component is not visible to the naked eye.

82273.name: Atria
82273.origin: Contraction of Bayer designation A(lpha) Tri(anguli) A(ustralis). The name is listed as "Alpha Tri. Aust." in 1951 American Nautical Almanac, but listed as "Atria" in 1952 version and subsequent versions.

110130.name: Lang-Exster
110130.origin: "Lang" is an Malayan/ Indonesian term meaning "hornbill", "Exster" is a Dutch word meaning "magpie" and both terms were used as name for the newly defined constellation in Early Modern Age by the Dutch sailors (de Houtman 1603) who artificially created the constellation as "Indian Magpie" referring to a species of bird with a strong cultural significance for the indigenous people they met (e.g. Dayak). The star is a spectroscopic binary which is why it makes sense to give it a double-name for the visible dot; the name may be split for the components later.

54061.name: Dubhe
54061.origin: Applied in medieval times from the Arabic constellation name al-dubb, "the Bear," for Ursa Major. The spelling in the oldest sources was edubh (corresponding to the Arabic noun with the article al prefixed as e).  Afterwards, by corruption, the initial e was transferred to the end of the word: dubhe.

53910.name: Merak
53910.origin: Applied in recent times from an abbreviation of its name for the Arabic Almagest period maraqq al-dubb al-akbar, "the Flank (or Groin) of the Greater Bear."

58001.name: Phecda
58001.origin: Applied in recent times from an abbreviation of its name for the Arabic Almagest period fakhidh al-dubb al-akbar, "the Thigh of the Greater Bear."

59774.name: Megrez
59774.origin: Applied in recent times from an abbreviation of its name for the Arabic Almagest period maghriz al-dubb al-akbar, "the Root (of the tail) of the Greater Bear."

62956.name: Alioth
62956.origin: Ultimately from its pre-Islamic Arabian name al-jaun, "the Black Horse, or Bull," which became corrupted even in Arabic sources (where some of the corruptions carried other meanings). For example, in the Arabic manuscript of the Almagest that was translated into Latin in 1175 A.D., this name of ε UMa had apparently been miswritten as al-jauza or al-jauza (the latter being identical to the name for the Arabic Almagest period for Orion and Gemini). Whatever was read in this Arabic manuscript was transliterated into Latin as alioze. In subsequent Latin copies, this name was further corrupted to aliore, Alcor, Alioth, etc. Since late medieval times, "Alioth" became the preferred name for ε UMa.

65378.name: Mizar
65378.origin: Ultimately from the Arabic word al-maraqq, "the Groin," used in the Arabic Almagest in describing β UMa. Correct transliterations of almaraqq in the Medieval Latin Almagest were mirac and mirach. However, Early Modern scholars confused these words with the Arabic word mi'zar, which had equally been transliterated and corrupted in Latin as mirac, mirach, etc. Subsequently the mistaken mi'zar, written as "Mizar," was applied as a star name to β UMa, and it became transferred to ζ UMa in late Early Modern times.

67301.name: Alkaid
67301.origin: Applied with various spellings since medieval times, from its pre-Islamic Arabian name al-qa'id, "the Leader" (probably as leader of the Daughters of the Bier).

44127.name: Talitha
44127.origin: Applied in recent times from an abbreviation of the pre-Islamic Arabian name alqafza al-thalitha, "the Third Leap," for ι and κ UMa. This pair, with the pairs λ/μ and v/ξ UMa, composed the pre-Islamic Arabian asterism qafazat al-ziba', "the Leaps of the Gazelles," imagined as the tracks left by those animals. In some later tradition, qafazat al-ziba' and adjacent asterisms were associated in a fable, where several gazelles leaped away from the Lion into a pond, leaving their tracks behind.

44471.name: Alkaphrah
44471.origin: corrupted spelling of Arabic القفزة al-qafzah "the leap" of the Indigenous Arabic group of gazelle asterisms preserved in Ibn Qutaybah.

50372.name: Tania Borealis
50372.origin: Applied in recent times from their pre-Islamic Arabian name al-qafza al-thaniya, "the Second Leap", and the Latin distinctions of "northern" and "southern," respectively.

50801.name: Tania Australis
50801.origin: Applied in recent times from their pre-Islamic Arabian name al-qafza al-thaniya, "the Second Leap", and the Latin distinctions of "northern" and "southern," respectively.

55219.name: Alula Borealis
55219.origin: Applied in recent times from their pre-Islamic Arabian name al-qafza al-ula, "the First Leap", and the Latin distinctions of "northern" and "southern," respectively.

41704.name: Muscida
41704.origin: Almagestum 1515: "illa quae est supra extremitatem Musciae" - Bayer (1603) "in naso, barbaris muscida." - attributed to "Barbarians"

57399.name: Taiyangshou
57399.origin: traditional Chinese single star asterism: Taiyangshou means "The Guardian of the Great Yang" and is the general in charge of the yang valve, symbolising Chief Minister. Xu, Pankenier and Jiang (2000) and Sun Shuwei (Stellarium) evaluating the medieval Song map, both identify chi UMa but Sun and Kistemaker (1997) studying the Han dynasty identify psi UMa.

11767.name: Polaris
11767.origin: A Latin adjective meaning "of the pole" (related to the noun polus, "the pole"). Applied as a star name to α UMi in Early Modern times, it reflects the star's temporary proximity to the north celestial pole.

72607.name: Kochab
72607.origin: Applied to β UMi in Early Modern times and of uncertam derivation. It is probably from one of the names Alrucaba, Rucaba, etc., that were first applied to θ UMa, then to α UMi, in medieval times. However, the name may also be from the Arabic word kaukab, or the Hebrew word kokhabh, both meaning "star."

75097.name: Pherkad
75097.origin: Applied in recent times from the singular form of the pre-Islamic Arabian asterism name al-farqadan, "the Two Calves," for β and γ UMi.

85822.name: Yildun
85822.origin: From the Turkish word yildiz, "star." In Early Modern times this common noun was erroneously said to be a Turkish name for the Pole Star (α UMi). Misspelled as "Yildun," the word was arbitrarily applied as a star name to δ UMi in recent times.

42913.name: Alsephina
42913.origin: The term is Arabic for "The Ship". It originates from the translation of Greek knowledge to Arabic when Argo Navis (The Ship Argo) was translated to Arabic and, thus, originally referred to the whole constellation rather than any specific star.

45941.name: Markeb
45941.origin: Evidently from the Arabic word markab, "a ship or any vehicle," presumably standing for the Greek constellation name Argo. However, Arabic sources do not mention markab for Argo, only al-safina ("the Ship"), hence the ultimate origin of the name remains a mystery. "Markeb" was applied as a star name to ρ Pup in medieval times, to κ Pup in Early Modern rimes, and finally to κ  Vel in recent times when Argo was divided into its four modern constellations

44816.name: Suhail
44816.origin: Applied in recent times and representing an abbreviation of any of several composite pre-Islamic Arabian names (for example suhail al-wazn, suhail al-muhlif) that Arabic authors variously attributed to brighter stars in the region of suhail. A Vel was among these brighter stars. Some of the composite names may have been authentic pre-Islamic Arabian names for far-southern stars, with their true identities unknown to the more northern Arabs, while others of them were surely the creations of pre-Islamic Arabian poets.

65474.name: Spica
65474.origin: Its ancient Roman name meaning "the Ear of Grain", after the star's Greek name στάχυς of identical meaning (in turn having obvious origins among the Babylonians and Sumerians). Reapplied in Early Modern times.

57757.name: Zavijava
57757.origin: From a contraction of the pre-Islamic Arabian name zawiyat al-'awwa', "the Angle of al-'awwa'," for γ Vir. Wrongly transferred to β Vir in recent times. The stars β, η, γ, and ε Vir marked the pre-Islamic Arabian lunar mansion al-'awwa' (with γ in its "angle"), but the meaning of al-'awwa' is unknown.

61941.name: Porrima
61941.origin: The name of a Roman goddess, one of several mythological names mentioned in connection with the constellation Virgo. Applied as a star name in recent times.

63090.name: Minelauva
63090.origin: The 13th Arabic lunar station bears the name العوا) Al-ʿAwwā, The bend. It consists of 5 stars: β, η, γ, δ and ε Vir. "Auva" or "Minelauva" are mediaeval transliterations of this name that now names one of its stars.

63608.name: Vindemiatrix
63608.origin: The formation of this name begins with the classical Greek name for this star: Protrygeter ("the Grape Gatherer") as it is given in the Almagest: ὁ βόρειος αὐτῶv καὶ καλούμενος Προτρυγητήρ. The Romans translated this name as vindemiator and other similiar masculine forms. Similarly, after a somewhat erroneous translation of the Greek name by the Arabs, the Medieval Latin translation in the Almagest was precedens vindemiatorem, "the One preceding the Grape Gatherer", modified in some editions of the Alphonsine Tables into precedens vindemitorem. The exact origin of the current, feminine "Vindemiatrix" from any of these forms is uncertain, but it first appeared in Early Modern times.

66249.name: Heze
66249.origin: Name of unknown etymology from the "Atlas Coeli Skalnaté Pleso" of Czech astronomer Antonín Bečvář (1901-1965). It could refer to God, possibly derived from Ezechiel (one of four prophets from Old Testament). Transcription to the Greek language adds "H" to EZE.

60129.name: Zaniah
60129.origin: From an abbreviation of the pre-Islamic Arabian name zawiyat al-'awwa', "the Angle of al-'awwa'," for γ Vir. Wrongly transferred to η Vir in recent times.

69701.name: Syrma
69701.origin: From the Greek word σύρμα, "train of a dress", used by Ptolemy in the Almagest in describing this star. The word was applied as a star name in recent times.

69427.name: Kang
69427.origin: determinitive star of lunar mansion Kang (The Neck) whose naming constellation constists of 4 stars according to sources back to the 3rd millennium BCE

69974.name: Khambalia
69974.origin: The Coptic (Egyptian) term Khambalia means "Crooked-clawed" (perhaps designating an agricultural device or symbol of secret knowledge); it was used in mantic texts for the star in the foot of Virgo.

70755.name: Elgafar
70755.origin: This name is a rare transliteration of Arabic الغفر al-ghafr (or "El-ġafr"), The Cover. This transliteration was used by Ideler (1809) but is uncommon today except in the Arabic Maghreb (northwest Africa). It is the name of the 15th lunar station (5 Oct).

95771.name: Anser
95771.origin: Johannes & Elisabetha Hevelius created “Vulpecula cum Ansere” (the Little Fox with the Goose) out of unformed stars in the space between Cygnus and Aquila. The constellation first appeared in Firmamentum Sobiescianum sive Uranographia (1687) and the accompanying introductory text, Prodromus astronomiae (1690). To emphasize that it was his own creation, Hevelius dedicated Figure L to the pair, shown as a detail in Fig. 3.1. In atlases published before Hevelius, its stars are shown simply marking the flow of the Milky Way through the area. Ian Ridpath (1989) noted that “Hevelius placed the fox near two other hunting animals, the eagle (the constellation Aquila) and the vulture (which was an alternative identification for Lyra). He explained that the fox was taking the goose to neighbouring Cerberus, another of his inventions.”unnamed before.

29997.name: Shangwei
29997.origin: Shàng Wèi (The Great Imperial Guard, 上衛) is the name of the fifth star on the right wall and the sixth star on the left wall of the Zǐ Gōng (Purple Palace, 紫宮) / Zǐwēi Yuán (Purple Forbidden Enclosure, 紫微垣), counting northward from the southern gate. Its corresponding star has changed many times throughout history.

14862.name: Shangcheng
14862.origin: Shàng Chéng (The Great Imperial Minister, 上丞) and Shào Chéng (The Second Imperial Minister, 少丞) are the two stars located to the left and right of the northern gate of the Zǐ Gōng (Purple Palace) / Zǐwēi Yuán (Purple Enclosure).

31940.name: Kamelos
31940.origin: "Kamelos" is Greek for camel, a pun with the name of the constellation "Camelopardalis" whose Latin term is a Greek loanword, literally meaning "checkered camel" = giraffe. On this base, Jacob Bartsch proposed 1624 "Camelus Rebeccae" as an alternative name for the constellation Camelopardalis, a reference to the story of Abraham's daughter-in-law, Rebecca.

17884.name: Custos
17884.origin: Custos Messium, the Harvest Keeper, was a constellation invented in Early Modern Time by the French astronomer Joseph Jérôme de Lalande (1732–1807) who might have punned with the name of his compatriot Charles Messier. Some European astronomers copied and translated it, though. The constellation became obsolete in the depolitisation of the IAU-sky and WGSN only resembles the Keeper, Custos.

9598.name: Gang
9598.origin: Gàng (“Shaft”) forms part of the ancient Chinese asterism of Huá Gài (Canopy of the Emperor, 華蓋). Allen (1899) mentions the term as a star name in Cam but WGSN places it in a correcter position.

9763.name: Rangifer
9763.origin: Rangifer, the Reindeer, is an extinct constellation first introduced by Pierre-Charles Le Monnier in 1743 in the book La Théorie des Comètes. He aimed to resemble an Indigenous constellation of the Sami people in Northern Scandinavia, where he had travelled to on a geodetic expedition.

5372.name: Tarandus
5372.origin: Tarandus is an alternative name for the Early Modern European constellation "Rangifer", the Reindeer, from Greek τάρανδος (reindeer), Latinised by Carl Linnaeus 1758 "Cervus Tarandus" for a species, Jamieson 1822 used "Rangifer tarandus" for the reindeer in the sky.

83100.name: Shengong
83100.origin: Shengong (神宫, Divine Palace) is a subsidiary asterism attached to the lodge Wěi (尾), Tail [of the Azure Dragon], located to the left of its determinative star and consisting of only one star (single star-asterism).

66006.name: Apamvatsa
66006.origin: Apāṃvatsa (अपऻऺवत्स), "calf of the waters" (or: "the smaller one"), is an Indian star name attested throughout the last millennium. The only indication of the position is Apamvatsa is 5° to the north of Citrā (चित्रा) (Spica) in Virgo, attested in several historical documents.

78322.name: Blaze Star
78322.origin: "Blaze Star" as a nickname for the recurrent nova T CrB has occurred in magazines since 1866. At that time, the physics of novae and supernovae was yet unknown, and the eruption of T CrB in 1866 was actually the first time of a naked-eye transient with spectroscopic evidence for hydrogen in the emission nebula. Recurrent Novae are a rare type of stars; only ten Galactic objects are known. T CrB is the prototype of T CrB-type recurrent novae which are contact binaries composed of a white dwarf orbiting a red giant.

301.name: Hydor
301.origin: The IAU-name "Hydor" resembles the original application of this name as a constellation in a vast area of faint stars in antiquity. It fits nicely the Indigenous Arabian constellation of "Safina", Ship. Note that the name "Hydor" was misapplied to a star in Aqr in the recent time. WGSN corrects this mistake. The Greek term "Hydor" (Ὕδωρ), Water, originally referred to a huge constellation, depicted around Cetus on ancient globes and described south of Aquarius in Aratus's poem of the 4th century BCE.

88267.name: Bodu
88267.origin: Bó Dù (帛度, “Textile Ruler”) is a Chinese asterism consisting of two stars, established by the Wuxian (巫咸) tradition during the Han dynasty. WGSN chose to adopt the name according to the Yi Shitong catalog because earlier identifications are highly uncertain.

88886.name: Ramus
88886.origin: Ramus, The Branch (of golden apples), is an addition to the early modern asterism Cerberus in Hercules. The name occurs in Bayer (1603) as a term but in depiction only later.

90139.name: Tusizuo
90139.origin: Tú Sì (屠肆, "Butcher's Shop") is a Chinese asterism consisting of two stars, established by the Wuxian (巫咸) school during the Han dynasty. As "Tusi" could be confused with other celestial bodies named Tusi after two Persian astronomers (asteroid (10269) Tusi and asteroid (7058) Al-Tusi), WGSN chose to add a determinative here. The chosen star 95 Her is "the left one in Tusi", in Chinese "Tusizuo", so WGSN adopts this name.

114570.name: Honores
114570.origin: The Latin term "Honores" means honour. A constellation introduced by Bode (1801). He had given a paper in 1790 that this was a joined decision by many European astronomers as a memorial to an extraordinarily generous patron of scientific research and benevolent, peaceful ruler. WGSN considers this message worth to convay even without the dedication to a specific person; we named a star in the feather "Honores" as there is a German proverb "Die Feder ist mächtiger als das Schwert" (the feather is mightier than the sword).

73695.name: Quadrans
73695.origin: Quadrans Muralis is an obsolete constellation invented in 1795 by the French astronomer Jérôme Lalande. WGSN decided to commemorate this constellation as it is the root of the name of the Quadrantide meteor shower that peaks in the first days of January.

114341.name: Safina
114341.origin: an Indigenous Arabic constellation of the Ship was between Diphda and Fomalhaut (see al Qutayba); WGSN picked one of the possible stars in the area. considering the close vicinity of the Greek star name "Hydor" (The Water) north of it, it becomes a sunken treasure ship.

72571.name: Solitaire
72571.origin: extinct constellations invented by Le Monnier (1776), Latinized "Turdus Solitarius", was originally meant to remember the extinct bird "Rodrigues Solitaire", but always depicted as a Blue Rock Thrush.

113288.name: Tengshe
113288.origin: Tengshe螣蛇 or 腾蛇 (Téng Shé, Flying Serpent) is a constellation created by ancient Chinese astrologers, dating back to the 2nd century BCE.

49637.name: Yunü
49637.origin: Yunü御女 is the star in the middle of the southernmost stars of the Xuanyuan轩辕 constellation. The correct transliteration is "Yunü".

61394.name: Phyllon Kissinou
61394.origin: Contemporary modern astronomers have used the nickname "Kissin"; therefore, the real name was made official. The term originates from the phrase "φύλλοv κισσίνου (phyllon kissinou, an ivy leaf)" in Ptolemy's Almagest. The star might be "multiple or double" according to SIMBAD, so long double name for the visible dot in the sky might be split up to the components later.

53524.name: Aiolos
53524.origin: Aiolos (Αίολος) was the Greek mythological keeper of the winds. In Homer’s Odyssey, Aiolos used an oxhide flask to capture all winds except for the western one, Zephyr. Zephyr then helped the sailboat of Ulysses navigate the seas towards home (Ithaca).

47780.name: Añañuca
47780.origin: Añañuca (Phycella cyrtanthoides) is the name of a red wildflower that grows from the Coquimbo region to the Maule region, whose colour alludes to that of the star GJ 367.

115211.name: Danfeng
115211.origin: Danfeng (丹凤) refers to the red phoenix, a sacred bird symbolising good fortune in ancient Chinese legend.

62452.name: Gar
62452.origin: “Gar” means flame in the Basque language.

65426.name: Matza
65426.origin: Matza refers to “a star in the sky” or “somebody that shines within” in the language of the Zoque people.

57087.name: Noquisi
57087.origin: “Noquisi” (ᏃᏈᏏ, No-Kwee-See) is the Cherokee word for “star”.

117883.name: Uúba
117883.cultural_group: Lenguistica U’wa language, also known as Tunebo.
117883.origin: Uúba is the word for “stars”, “seeds”, and “eyes” in the Lenguistica U’wa language (Tunebo) of the U’wa Indigenous community of Colombia.

90004.name: Alasia
90004.origin: Alasia is the first historically recorded name of Cyprus, dating back to mid-fifteenth century BCE.

29550.name: Amadioha
29550.origin: Amadioha is the god of thunder in Igbo mythology. As well as representing justice, Amadioha is also a god of love, peace and unity.

57820.name: Aniara
57820.origin: Aniara is the name of a spaceship in the epic poem Aniara by Swedish author Harry Martinson.

72845.name: Arcalís
72845.origin: Arcalis is a famous peak in the north of Andorra, where the Sun passes through a hole in the mountain twice a year at fixed dates. It was used as a primitive solar calendar and reference point for shepherds and early inhabitants of Andorra.

118319.name: Axólotl
118319.origin: Axólotl means water animal in the native Nahuatl language, which is a unique and culturally significant endemic amphibious species from the basin of Mexico.

13993.name: Ayeyarwady
13993.origin: Ayeyarwady is the largest and most important river in Myanmar.

73136.name: Baekdu
73136.origin: Baekdu is the highest mountain on the Korean peninsula, situated in North Korea, and symbolises the national spirit of Korea.

95124.name: Belel
95124.origin: Belel is a rare source of water in the north of Senegal.

6643.name: Bélénos
6643.origin: Bélénos was the god of light, of the Sun, and of health in Gaulish mythology.

48711.name: Bibhā
48711.origin: Bibhā [/bɪbɦa/] is the Bengali pronunciation of the Sanskrit word Vibha, which means a bright beam of light.

107251.name: Bosona
107251.origin: Bosona is the name given to the territory of Bosnia in the 10th century. Later, the name was transformed to Bosnia originating from the name of the Bosna river.

26380.name: Bubup
26380.origin: Bubup is the Boonwurrung word for child.

12191.name: Buna
12191.origin: Buna is the commonly used word for coffee in Ethiopia.

37284.name: Ceibo
37284.origin: Ceibo is the name of the native tree of Uruguay that gives rise to the national flower.

99894.name: Chechia
99894.origin: Chechia is a flat-surfaced, traditional red wool hat worn by men and women, symbolising the country's rich traditions and is considered as the national headdress for in Tunisia.

1547.name: Citadelle
1547.origin: The Citadelle is a large mountaintop fortress in Nord, Haiti built after Haiti's independence, and was designated a UNESCO World Heritage site along with the nearby Sans-Souci Palace.

33719.name: Citalá
33719.origin: Citalá means River of stars in the native Nahuat language.

3479.name: Cocibolca
3479.origin: Cocibolca is the Nahualt name for the largest lake in Central America in Nicaragua.

54158.name: Dingolay
54158.origin: Dingolay means to dance, twist and turn in elaborate movements, symbolising the culture and language of the ancestors of the people of Trinidad and Tobago.

66047.name: Dofida
66047.origin: Dofida means our star in Nias language.

114322.name: Ebla
114322.origin: Ebla was one of the earliest kingdoms in Syria, and served as a prominent region in the 2nd and 3rd millenia B.C.

5529.name: Emiw
5529.origin: Emiw represents love in the local Makhuwa language of the northern region of Mozambique.

2247.name: Felixvarela
2247.origin: Felix Varela (1788–1853) was the first to teach science in Cuba at the San Carlos and San Ambrosio Seminary. He opened the way to education for all, and began the experimental teaching of physics in Cuba.

57370.name: Flegetonte
57370.origin: Flegetonte is the underworld river of fire from Greek Mythology in the Italian narrative poem on the afterlife "Divina Commedia" (Divine Commedy) by Dante Alighieri, chosen as an allusion to the star's fiery nature.

56508.name: Formosa
56508.origin: Formosa is the historical name of Taiwan used in the 17th century, meaning beautiful in Latin.

61177.name: Funi
61177.origin: Funi is an old Icelandic word meaning fire or blaze.

42446.name: Gakyid
42446.origin: Gakyid means happiness. Gross National Happiness is the development philosophy conceived and followed in Bhutan and is one of Bhutan's contributions to the world.

94645.name: Gumala
94645.origin: Gumala is a Malay word, which means a magic bezoar stone found in snakes, dragons, etc.

21109.name: Hoggar
21109.origin: Hoggar is the name of the main mountain range in the Sahara Desert in southern Algeria.

55174.name: Hunahpú
55174.origin: Hunahpú was one of the twin gods who became the Sun in K'iche' (Quiché) Mayan mythology as recounted in the Popol Vuh.

80076.name: Hunor
80076.origin: Hunor was a legendary ancestor of the Huns and the Hungarian nation, and brother of Magor.

47087.name: Illyrian
47087.origin: Historians largely believe that the Albanians are descendants of the Illyrians, a term Albanians proudly call themselves.

84787.name: Inquill
84787.origin: Inquill was one half of the couple involved in the tragic love story Way to the Sun by famous Peruvian writer Abraham Valdelomar.

15578.name: Intan
15578.origin: Intan means diamond in the Malay language (Bahasa Melayu), alluding to the shining of a star.

108375.name: Itonda
108375.origin: Itonda, in the Myene tongue, corresponds to all that is beautiful.

47202.name: Kalausi
47202.origin: The word Kalausi means a very strong whirling column of wind in the Dholuo language of Kenya.

79219.name: Kamuy
79219.origin: Kamuy is a word in the Ainu language denoting a supernatural entity possessing spiritual energy.

76351.name: Karaka
76351.origin: Karaka is the word in the Māori language for a plant endemic to New Zealand that produces a bright orange, fleshy fruit.

92895.name: Kaveh
92895.origin: Kaveh is one of the heroes of Shahnameh, the epic poem composed by Persian poet Ferdowsi between 977 and 1010 CE. Kaveh is a blacksmith who symbolises justice.

12961.name: Koeia
12961.origin: Koeia was the word for star in the language of the Taíno Indigenous People of the Caribbean.

66192.name: Liesma
66192.origin: Liesma means flame, and it is the name of a character from the Latvian poem Staburags un Liesma.

110813.name: Lionrock
110813.origin: Lion Rock is a lion-shaped peak overlooking Hong Kong and is a cultural symbol with deep respect from the local community.

30860.name: Lucilinburhuc
30860.origin: The Lucilinburhuc fortress was built in 963 by the founder of Luxembourg, Count Siegfried.

30905.name: Lusitânia
30905.origin: Lusitânia is the ancient name of the western region of the Iberic Peninsula where the Lusitanian people lived and where most of modern-day Portugal is situated.

52521.name: Macondo
52521.origin: Macondo is the mythical village of the novel One Hundred Years of Solitude (Cien años de soledad) the classic novel by Gabriel García Marquez. Macondo is a fictional place where magic and reality are mixed.

24003.name: Mago
24003.origin: Mago is a National Park in Ethiopia noted for its giraffes. The star also happens to be in the constellation of Camelopardis (the giraffe).

82651.name: Mahsati
82651.origin: Mahsati Ganjavi (1089–1159) is one of the brightest shining stars of Azerbaijani poetry. She was said to have associated with both Omar Khayyam and Nizami and was well educated and talented and played numerous musical instruments.

72339.name: Mönch
72339.origin: Mönch is one of the prominent peaks of the Bernese Alps in Switzerland.

22491.name: Mouhoun
22491.origin: Mouhoun, also called Volta Noire, is the largest river in Burkina Faso and plays an important role in the lives of the people in the areas it passes through.

40687.name: Násti
40687.origin: Násti means star in the Northern Sami language of Norway.

48235.name: Natasha
48235.origin: Natasha means "thank you" in many languages of Zambia.

5054.name: Nenque
5054.origin: Nenque means the Sun in the language spoken by the Indigenous Waorani tribes of the Amazon regions of Ecuador.

32916.name: Nervia
32916.origin: Nervia, adapted from Nervii, was a prominent Belgian Celtic tribe.

74961.name: Nikawiy
74961.origin: Nikawiy is the word for mother in the Indigenous Cree language of Canada.

31895.name: Nosaxa
31895.origin: Nosaxa means spring in the Moqoit language. The word comes from a combination of nosahuec, which means renew, and ñaaxa, which means year.

13192.name: Nushagak
13192.origin: Nushagak is a regional river near Dilingham, Alaska, which is famous for its wild salmon that sustain local Indigenous communities.

99711.name: Phoenicia
99711.origin: Phoenicia was an ancient thalassocratic civilisation of the Mediterranean that originated from the area of modern-day Lebanon.

88414.name: Pincoya
88414.origin: Pincoya is a female water spirit from southern Chilean mythology who is said to bring drowned sailors to the Caleuche so that they can live in the afterlife.

116084.name: Poerava
116084.origin: Poerava is the word in the Cook Islands Maori language for a large mystical black pearl of utter beauty and perfection.

83547.name: Rapeto
83547.origin: Rapeto is a giant creature from Malagasy tales.

81022.name: Rosalíadecastro
81022.origin: Rosalia de Castro was a significant figure of Galician culture and prominent Spanish writer, whose pioneeting work often referenced the night and celestial objects.

56572.name: Sagarmatha
56572.origin: Sagarmatha is the Nepali name for the highest peak in the world (also known as Mount Everest) and symbol of national pride of Nepal.

106824.name: Sāmaya
106824.origin: Sāmaya means peace in the Sinhalese language.

55664.name: Shama
55664.origin: Shama is an Urdu literary term meaning a small lamp or flame, symbolic of the light of the star.

79431.name: Sharjah
79431.origin: Sharjah is the cultural capital of United Arab Emirates, and considered the city of knowledge due to its many educational centers, institutes, museums, libraries and heritage centers.

95262.name: Sika
95262.origin: Sika means gold in the Ewe language and gold is one of Ghana's principal exports.

104780.name: Solaris
104780.origin: Solaris is the title of a 1961 science fiction novel about an ocean-covered exoplanet by Polish writer Stanislaw Lem.

43674.name: Stribor
43674.origin: Stribor is God of winds in Slavic mythology, as well as a literature character in the book Priče iz davnine (Croatian Tales of Long Ago) by the Croatian author Ivana Brlić-Mažuranić.

38041.name: Tapecue
38041.origin: Tapecue means eternal path in Guarani and represents the Milky Way through which the first inhabitants of the Earth arrived and could return.

80687.name: Timir
80687.origin: Timir means darkness in Bengali language, alluding to the star being far away in the darkness of space.

60644.name: Tupã
60644.origin: Tupã is one of four principle gods of the Guarani Cosmogony in popular Paraguayan folklore that helped the supreme god Ñamandu to create the Universe.

17096.name: Tupi
17096.origin: Tupi is the name of the most populous Indigenous People living on the eastern coast of South America, before the Portuguese arrived in the 16th century.

57291.name: Uklun
57291.origin: Uklun means us or we in the Pitkern language of the people of Pitcairn Islands.

96078.name: Uruk
96078.origin: Uruk was an ancient city of the Sumer and Babylonian civilizations in Mesopotamia situated along an ancient channel of the Euphrates river in modern-day Iraq.

91852.name: Xihe
91852.origin: Xihe (羲和) is the goddess of the sun in the Chinese mythology and also represents the earliest astronomers and developers of calendars in ancient China.

84405.name: Guniibuu
84405.origin: Guniibuu is the Kamilaroi/Euahlayi name for the robin red-breast bird (Petroica boodang). A traditional story links Guniibuu with Gidjirrigaa (Budgerigar) the star κ Sco.

62223.name: La Superba
62223.origin: In 1868 Secchi used "superba" as an adjective to describe the star Y CVn, not as a proper name of the star. However, in 1876 Birmingham seems to have borrowed from Secchi this term and used it as a proper name of the star. As a consequence, in 1877 Secchi himself adopted the same name. Agnes Clerke attributed the term to Secchi, without distinguishing between the adjective and the name. In principle, it should be attributed to both Secchi and Birmingham, in my opinion.

86782.name: Alruba
86782.origin: Arabic الربع Al Rubaʽ translates "the foal" and specifically refers to a young camel born in the spring. The name was considered traditional by WGSN in 2018 as it is listed in Allen (1899).

48615.name: Felis
48615.origin: Felis (The Cat) is the name of a constellation invented by Lalande. The name is applied to one star in the area that the constellation covered.

13061.name: Lilii Borea
13061.origin: Lacaille used the now obsolete constellation Lilium (The Lily) and named this star "in the north of Lily", in Latin: Lilii Borea

41075.name: Alsciaukat
41075.origin: misspelled Arabic الشوكة aš-šawkat (al-shaukat), The Thorn. The name obviously has nothing to do with the figure of the lynx (or historically sometimes called "Tiger" or "Tigris") that was invented in Early Modern Times.

13209.name: Bharani
13209.origin: the Indian term (Sanscrit: भरणी), The Bearer, designates the 2nd of the 27 nakshatras consisting of the three stars 35, 39 and 41 Ari, among which 41 Ari is the brightest. The modern star name was given to the brightest star of the historical constellation.

87261.name: Fuyue
87261.origin: traditional Chinese single star asterism: a legendary wise minister of the Yin or Shang dynasty, 18th century BCE. According to Rufus and Tien (1945), sometimes called the invocator (regarding faults). Sun and Kistemaker (1997) quote Sima Qian that Fu Yue was a chancellor of Emperor Wu Ding of the Yin dynasty but they admit that the could also represent a shaman in the royal harem helping to produce sons. The ancient star name is typically identified with the bright star G Sco.

53229.name: Praecipua
53229.origin: Piazzi (1814) in his star catalogue introduced this proper name for the star because Hevelius (1690) had added the adjective "praecipua" (Chief) as a description of this star.

21594.name: Sceptrum
21594.origin: from the obsolete constellation of Sceptrum Brandenburgicum

63076.name: Taiyi
63076.origin: single star asterism: August Unity, Supreme One

62423.name: Tianyi
62423.origin: Chinese single star asterism: heavenly unity

87937.name: Barnard's Star
87937.origin: Named after American astronomer E. E. Barnard who first measured the record high proper motion for this star in 1916, the name started appearing in the astronomical literature in the follow-up studies of the star and came into common use starting in the 1920s.

72487.name: Merga
72487.origin: A Latin word meaning "reaping hook," used in a Early Modern discussion of the constellation Bootes. According to this discussion, some classical sources mentioned a reaping hook held in Bootes' hand opposite the staff. Subsequently the word was applied as a star name to hBoo.

17579.name: Asterope
17579.origin: These names were individually applied in Early Modern times from a family of characters in Greek mythology: Atlas, Pleione and their seven daughters, the Pleiades.

17847.name: Atlas
17847.origin: These names were individually applied in Early Modern times from a family of characters in Greek mythology: Atlas, Pleione and their seven daughters, the Pleiades.

17489.name: Celaeno
17489.origin: These names were individually applied in Early Modern times from a family of characters in Greek mythology: Atlas, Pleione and their seven daughters, the Pleiades.

17499.name: Electra
17499.origin: These names were individually applied in Early Modern times from a family of characters in Greek mythology: Atlas, Pleione and their seven daughters, the Pleiades.

17531.name: Taygeta
17531.origin: These names were individually applied in Early Modern times from a family of characters in Greek mythology: Atlas, Pleione and their seven daughters, the Pleiades.

17573.name: Maia
17573.origin: These names were individually applied in Early Modern times from a family of characters in Greek mythology: Atlas, Pleione and their seven daughters, the Pleiades.

17608.name: Merope
17608.origin: These names were individually applied in Early Modern times from a family of characters in Greek mythology: Atlas, Pleione and their seven daughters, the Pleiades.

58952.name: Tonatiuh
58952.origin: Tonatiuh was the Aztec god of the Sun.

65477.name: Alcor
65477.origin: Ultimately from the pre-Islamic Arabian name al-jaun, for ε UMa, which was transliterated and eventually corrupted in Latin to "Alcor." The name was wrongly transferred to 80 UMa in Early Modern times.

17851.name: Pleione
17851.origin: These names were individually applied in Early Modern times from a family of characters in Greek mythology: Atlas, Pleione and their seven daughters, the Pleiades.

53721.name: Chalawan
53721.origin: Chalawan is a mythological crocodile king from a Thai folktale.

90344.name: Fafnir
90344.origin: Fafnir was a Norse mythological dwarf who turned into a dragon.

113357.name: Helvetios
113357.origin: Helvetios is the Latin for "the Helvetian" and refers to the Celtic tribe that lived in Switzerland during the Middle Ages.

46471.name: Intercrus
46471.origin: Intercrus means "between the legs" in Latin style, referring to the star's position in the constellation Ursa Major.

80838.name: Ogma
80838.origin: Ogma was a deity of eloquence, writing, and great physical strength in the Celtic mythologies of Ireland and Scotland, and may be related to the Gallo-Roman deity "Ogmios".

116076.name: Veritate
116076.origin: From the latin "Veritas", truth. The ablative form means "where there is truth".
